The examination of the radiation patterns of the antennas in this paper formed a study of dynamic range of both FDTD and MoM for objects with a broad angular region of low response. They showed that FDTD and MoM can both pick up sharp nulls in radiation patterns that are caused by cancellation of field values. The low-response region of the horn antenna studied was both very broad and also very gradual. In a region such as this, where the far fields are 50 dB down from peak values, power levels are a factor of $10^{-5}$ down. This implied required accuracy in the electric and magnetic fields was approximately 0.3 $\%$, to effectively model these low fields emanating in this direction. They demonstrated that the FDTD technique is valid for use in modeling of radiating structures.

