They discussed several important issues affecting computational dynamic range. From the discussion of the $26.6^\circ$ horn, they concluded that neither MoM nor the then FDTD techniques could be blindly applied to antennas or scatterers which have a broad angular range of far fields lower than -40 dB relative to the main lobe or the incident beam. Changing the FDTD gridding to a finer spatial sampling, using brute-force methods to eliminate the effects of the radiation boundary conditions (RBC)\rq s, and calculating the best integration from the near-field points were found to be ways to achieve more accurate results, and hence, greater dynamic range. However, this reasoning was stated to be valid only in two dimensions.

In the case of three dimensions, they noted that MoM matrix size would increase by an order of magnitude and cause the inversion or solution time to increase by three orders of magnitude. For the FDTD code, time-gating out the RBC reflections was found to be impractical, because it increased the volume of space in which the time marching takes place and was much worse than simply increasing the area in two dimensions. As the fields change in three dimensions, going from an $r^{-0.5}$ dependence to an $r^{-1}$ dependence, it was hoped that this would reduce the negative effects of the RBC\rq s because the fields would be weaker upon reaching the grid boundaries. Also it was pointed out that for antenna problems, FDTD and MoM are similar in that after one large solution is worked out (time marching of fields or matrix inversion,) finding the antenna pattern was simply a matter of a number of integrations or a number of matrix multiplications.

